WEBVTT

00:09.500 --> 00:13.360
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:29.020 --> 00:34.320
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.160 --> 00:38.620
And here are your hosts.

00:42.780 --> 00:43.920
This is Daryl Lane.

00:44.160 --> 00:44.820
And David Carson.

00:45.320 --> 00:49.000
Ray Bradbury is a name familiar not to just readers of science fiction or fantasy, but

00:49.000 --> 00:50.760
to almost any literate American or European.

00:51.360 --> 00:55.800
Some of Bradbury's work, like the Martian Chronicles or Fahrenheit 451, are classics

00:55.800 --> 00:58.240
that are admired by readers of all kinds and of all tastes.

00:58.720 --> 01:03.700
He does indeed write science fiction, and fantasy, and horror, and weird stories, but

01:03.700 --> 01:06.820
they're all done with a style and emotional texture that is unique to Bradbury.

01:07.480 --> 01:11.760
Bradbury wrote from a very early age, as far back as his grammar school days in the Midwest.

01:12.320 --> 01:16.180
But it wasn't until he was 19 and living in Los Angeles that he got the push that helped

01:16.180 --> 01:16.820
him to get published.

01:17.360 --> 01:20.720
He tells us about a group of science fiction writers in Los Angeles that gave him that

01:20.720 --> 01:21.000
push.

01:22.180 --> 01:26.900
Bruce Yerke, who was the secretary for the Science Fantasy Society, wrote me a letter

01:26.900 --> 01:28.840
in October of 1937.

01:28.840 --> 01:31.020
That was my last year in high school.

01:31.400 --> 01:35.500
They invited me to come down to Clifton's cafeteria and meet the group.

01:36.040 --> 01:39.500
And I was very shy and a little fearful.

01:39.660 --> 01:40.500
I didn't know anyone.

01:41.120 --> 01:46.580
But nevertheless, I got my courage together and went down to a meeting.

01:47.220 --> 01:52.460
And that was my first encounter with Forrest Ackerman, who became my first editor.

01:52.740 --> 01:55.280
He was editing a magazine called Imagination.

01:55.280 --> 02:01.900
And then along over the next year or so, I met Henry Kupner, Arthur Barnes, Lee Brackett,

02:02.040 --> 02:06.560
Robert Heinlein, Jack Williamson, Ross Rockland, Henry Hasse.

02:07.340 --> 02:08.900
They all became friends.

02:09.500 --> 02:12.320
And in one way or another, influenced me.

02:12.480 --> 02:13.920
We were very close.

02:14.260 --> 02:19.360
And I was beginning to write a lot of very bad science fiction, very bad fantasy.

02:19.580 --> 02:21.040
I still haven't learned to write well.

02:21.720 --> 02:23.960
But these people were very patient with me.

02:23.960 --> 02:32.480
And especially, I remember Robert Heinlein and his wonderful wife, who invited me up

02:32.480 --> 02:33.740
to their home on occasion.

02:34.260 --> 02:39.100
I got to read a lot of his manuscripts before they were published.

02:39.260 --> 02:40.360
He was just starting to write.

02:41.120 --> 02:50.780
He came to a meeting at the Science Fantasy Club in, I believe it was 19, early 30, 38

02:50.780 --> 02:51.520
or 39.

02:52.120 --> 02:56.220
He had just written his first story and sold it to a stunning science fiction.

02:56.740 --> 03:00.940
So he was a beginner, just as I was, except he was about 11 years older.

03:01.000 --> 03:03.000
He was around, I would say, 31.

03:03.040 --> 03:05.160
And I think I was 19 when I met him.

03:06.000 --> 03:12.820
So it was that kind of situation where you had personal contact with writers who were

03:12.820 --> 03:15.600
already established or were establishing themselves.

03:16.300 --> 03:19.380
And of course, it changed my life forever because I had acceptance.

03:20.000 --> 03:24.800
People were willing to put up with me and read my terrible stories.

03:26.660 --> 03:30.220
Though Bradbury did get encouragement from these other writers, his fiction has always

03:30.220 --> 03:31.240
been uniquely his own.

03:31.780 --> 03:34.280
We asked him if it would be fair to call him a self-taught writer.

03:35.200 --> 03:36.680
Well, I guess you can say that.

03:37.780 --> 03:41.140
Most writing, almost every art form, is self-teaching.

03:41.560 --> 03:45.120
Except what you need around the edges is shortcut.

03:45.120 --> 03:52.400
If people can help you by recommending certain books, either books on writing or books which

03:52.400 --> 03:55.520
give you examples of excellent writing.

03:55.740 --> 04:00.720
I remember Henry Kutner was always calling Lee Brackett up or calling me up and saying,

04:00.800 --> 04:02.440
hey, have you read Captain Adam Porter?

04:02.900 --> 04:04.620
Do you know the work of John Collier?

04:05.080 --> 04:06.680
What about Yudor O'Welty?

04:06.840 --> 04:13.200
Well, this kind of shortcut is so important that you break away from your own field and

04:13.200 --> 04:18.960
move on out into the wide culture and bring back into the science fiction and the fantasy

04:18.960 --> 04:25.560
field influences from people like Kipling or Somerset Mom or John Collier.

04:26.200 --> 04:30.640
So that's where having a good teacher is important.

04:31.520 --> 04:37.320
Not that they teach you all that much or that intensely, but the fact that they care about

04:37.320 --> 04:43.760
you at all is very good for your sense of malnutrition.

04:44.120 --> 04:48.880
We all feel as if we haven't set ourselves well enough from here at that age.

04:50.600 --> 04:53.220
We'll continue our conversation with Ray Bradbury next time.

