06:12.660 --> 06:17.800
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:20.600 --> 06:22.160
And here are your hosts.

06:26.620 --> 06:27.660
This is David Carson.

06:27.920 --> 06:28.600
And Darrell Lane.

06:28.900 --> 06:32.360
Ray Bradbury is an internationally known author who's managed to attract readers outside

06:32.360 --> 06:34.080
the field of science fiction and fantasy.

06:34.080 --> 06:38.100
In fact, he's one of the few writers of science fiction and fantasy whose name is almost instantly

06:38.100 --> 06:39.640
recognizable outside the field.

06:40.180 --> 06:43.900
He's also written so-called mainstream, or regular fiction ever since he began publishing

06:43.900 --> 06:45.640
early in the 1940s.

06:45.760 --> 06:50.080
Dan DeLion Wine, a poetic novel about a boy growing up in a small Midwestern town, is

06:50.080 --> 06:51.880
one example of his non-science fiction output.

06:52.240 --> 06:55.920
We asked him how he broke out of the restricted field of science fiction and gained such widespread

06:55.920 --> 06:59.000
acceptance for all of his fiction with all types of readers.

07:00.320 --> 07:03.860
Well, you just automatically think about it for a lifetime.

07:04.200 --> 07:11.260
I always dreamt of being, number one, a writer, not a writer of science fiction or a writer

07:11.260 --> 07:12.920
of fantasy, but a writer period.

07:13.120 --> 07:19.740
I had huge heroes that I looked up to in the world, people like Shakespeare and a lot of

07:19.740 --> 07:24.060
the great poets, Emily Dickinson and Robert Frost when I was in 19th.

07:24.580 --> 07:29.900
And then as I got older and began to see the world of the theater around me more, I wanted

07:29.900 --> 07:31.100
to do theater work.

07:31.520 --> 07:33.060
I loved motion pictures.

07:33.380 --> 07:35.840
I knew that eventually I wanted to do some films.

07:36.360 --> 07:41.280
So my interests were always very Catholic, very broad, and it was only a matter of time

07:41.280 --> 07:43.740
before I would experiment with each of these things.

07:44.200 --> 07:50.600
And at the same time I was writing and having my first success in selling stories to Weirdtales,

07:50.960 --> 07:57.760
I was beginning to write short stories in the larger fields, stories about racial relationships

07:57.760 --> 08:01.080
or stories about travel inside America.

08:01.760 --> 08:04.560
A little bit of everything I was experimenting with.

08:05.380 --> 08:09.140
Bradbury said he was about 25 when he first began publishing stories that were not science

08:09.140 --> 08:09.960
fiction or fantasy.

08:10.880 --> 08:16.740
A friend of mine called me on the phone and said he was going to Mexico to travel for

08:16.740 --> 08:17.360
two months.

08:17.600 --> 08:18.640
Did I want to come along?

08:18.640 --> 08:20.220
Well, I said I can't.

08:20.300 --> 08:21.020
I don't have any money.

08:21.240 --> 08:26.380
I was still only making around $20 a week selling stories to Weirdtales.

08:26.760 --> 08:33.600
I usually sold six stories to Weirdtales every year, which gave me around $120 for the whole

08:33.600 --> 08:33.920
year.

08:34.560 --> 08:38.800
And then I sold an occasional murder mystery and a few science fiction stories.

08:38.900 --> 08:43.820
So my income at the time was around $2,500 a year if I was lucky.

08:44.780 --> 08:47.040
And he said, oh, you're such a coward.

08:47.040 --> 08:49.120
He said, here the war is over.

08:49.780 --> 08:52.260
War has been over in Europe a month or so.

08:52.960 --> 08:57.460
You should travel and you're afraid to send out your short stories.

08:57.620 --> 08:58.660
You're afraid of being rejected.

08:59.280 --> 09:06.500
I know you've got a lot of excellent broad literary middle stream fictions.

09:06.940 --> 09:08.860
I'm not sure we type them and send them out.

09:09.140 --> 09:13.280
So by God, he egged me on and I got three short stories out of my files.

09:13.780 --> 09:17.120
I re-typed them, put an assumed name on each one, William Elliott.

09:17.760 --> 09:23.840
I mailed them off without an agent, without any representation, with not even a letter

09:24.760 --> 09:26.320
from myself to the editors.

09:26.760 --> 09:31.780
And one story to Charm, one story to Mademoiselle, and another one to Collier's.

09:32.620 --> 09:36.280
Bradbury got a big surprise and a big paycheck after sending those three stories in.

09:37.180 --> 09:40.280
Well, all three stories sold within three days of each other.

09:40.760 --> 09:48.220
One story sold on August 19th to Charm, on the 20th, one to Mademoiselle, and on my birthday,

09:48.220 --> 09:52.140
the 22nd of August, I sold my first short story to Collier's.

09:52.440 --> 09:57.500
So all of a sudden, I had an aggregate of $1,000 which arrived in the mail.

09:57.980 --> 10:06.260
Well, $1,000 back in 1945 would be like getting $15,000 in the mail today.

10:06.580 --> 10:07.880
I was out of my head.

10:07.940 --> 10:08.720
I couldn't believe it.

10:09.120 --> 10:14.360
So without money, I picked up and went to Mexico with him for six weeks, where I had

10:14.360 --> 10:19.120
a whole series of adventures that scared the hell out of me and caused me to write some

10:19.120 --> 10:21.740
of my best weird stories when I came home.

10:22.320 --> 10:27.400
So that's the way I made the transition, because someone called me a coward and dared me to

10:27.400 --> 10:28.480
send my stories out.

10:29.560 --> 10:31.700
On our next show, we'll have more with Ray Bradbury.

