12:03.540 --> 12:04.980
And here are your hosts.

12:09.320 --> 12:11.420
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane.

12:11.740 --> 12:15.260
Ray Bradbury's The Martian Chronicles is one of the best known science fiction books produced

12:15.260 --> 12:15.920
in this country.

12:16.500 --> 12:20.660
It's poetic style, it's treatment of mankind's present problems, and its vision of man's

12:20.660 --> 12:24.120
future make it a book admired not only by regular readers of science fiction, but by

12:24.120 --> 12:25.000
anyone who reads it all.

12:25.480 --> 12:29.160
The book is really a collection of related short stories concerning man's colonization

12:29.160 --> 12:29.680
of Mars.

12:29.680 --> 12:33.320
We asked Bradbury if he wrote each story with the entire volume in mind.

13:02.860 --> 13:09.480
Well, I had meetings with various people at Simon & Schuster and Doubleday, and they

13:09.480 --> 13:13.060
all said, look, we don't publish short stories, nobody buys them, nobody cares.

13:13.740 --> 13:19.400
And then one night I had dinner with Walter Bradbury at Doubleday, no relation to me,

13:19.980 --> 13:25.280
a wonderful gentleman, very bright gentleman, and sitting there at dinner that night he

13:25.280 --> 13:27.200
said, Ray, what about all those Martian stories?

13:27.200 --> 13:28.960
Isn't there a novel there?

13:29.060 --> 13:31.680
Isn't there some way of hanging them all together?

13:31.900 --> 13:33.500
It seems to me there's a common thread.

13:33.900 --> 13:40.660
I said, oh my God, you know, years ago I made notes about doing a series of chronicles,

13:40.740 --> 13:43.220
and then threw the notes somewhere and forgot about them.

13:43.480 --> 13:48.820
So my subconscious must have remembered, and along through the years was putting these

13:48.820 --> 13:50.280
beads on a single thread.

13:50.720 --> 13:57.100
I went back to the YMCA that night, sat in my underwear, it was a hot, hot summer evening

13:57.100 --> 14:02.520
terribly humid, and finished typing out an outline of a book which I called The Martian

14:02.520 --> 14:07.980
Chronicles, which I then took to Doubleday the next day, and they promptly bought the

14:07.980 --> 14:11.260
novel, plus the illustrated man, a collection of stories.

14:11.940 --> 14:18.720
And I left New York City with, again, a fabulous $1,000, $500 for each book.

14:19.280 --> 14:21.380
The stories are not scientifically accurate.

14:21.800 --> 14:25.360
Man can breathe the Martian atmosphere unaided, for example, but they're not meant to be.

14:25.360 --> 14:29.520
They have to be read symbolically, at a deep unconscious level which is triggered by

14:29.520 --> 14:30.860
Bradbury's poetic way of writing.

14:31.520 --> 14:34.460
There is an order to the 26 stories that make up The Martian Chronicles.

14:34.940 --> 14:39.220
The final one is entitled The Million-Year Picnic, and we ask Bradbury why he put that one last.

14:40.060 --> 14:41.860
It seemed a proper place to put it.

14:42.920 --> 14:49.740
It seemed a culmination of all the stories, and that my job in looking at all my stories

14:49.740 --> 14:54.280
was to guess where to place each, and well, some of them it was very easy.

14:54.280 --> 14:59.300
I did a whole series of stories of first encounters on Mars with various expeditions.

14:59.640 --> 15:05.460
So I knew those automatically had to be up front, along with an imaginary encounter in

15:05.460 --> 15:09.120
Illa, where a woman dreams an invasion of Mars.

15:09.640 --> 15:15.140
We never see the invasion itself of the Earthmen, but we know that secretly it must be there

15:15.140 --> 15:18.140
somewhere, and the real people got killed by the jealous husband.

15:18.920 --> 15:23.860
And then you go along through all the other encounters, and what happens to Mars as a result,

15:23.860 --> 15:32.700
of the invasion by Earth people, and ending with all of your final beats, and a brief return to Earth

15:32.700 --> 15:37.520
for there will come soft rains, and then The Million-Year Picnic at the end.

15:37.620 --> 15:44.180
It all stalled together in roughly two hours in my head at the typewriter that night at the YMCA.

15:45.420 --> 15:49.980
In 1980, NBC produced a major six-hour dramatization of The Martian Chronicles.

15:50.340 --> 15:52.060
We asked Bradbury if he was happy with it.

15:53.340 --> 15:54.980
I most certainly was not.

15:55.460 --> 16:00.980
It was one of the most boring shows ever put on television, and it's a great shame.

16:01.240 --> 16:07.960
Obviously no one enjoyed doing it, and the director obviously didn't enjoy it, which is a great shame,

16:08.100 --> 16:13.060
because he should have got out of bed every morning and said, let's have a ball, let's play,

16:13.700 --> 16:19.920
let's jump up and down and scream and yell and get something out of this material, but he obviously didn't do that.

16:19.920 --> 16:22.740
We'll have more for you, Bradbury, on our next show.

