17:59.740 --> 18:04.500
Ray Bradbury's 1962 novel, Something Wicked This Way Comes, is a classic of fantasy and horror.

18:04.980 --> 18:10.580
It's about a carnival that comes to a small Midwestern town, a carnival with evil secrets beneath its colorful exterior,

18:11.040 --> 18:12.800
and about two boys who discover the evil.

18:13.300 --> 18:16.100
We asked Bradbury if there was a particular impetus behind the story.

18:16.680 --> 18:19.200
Not really. It all started a long time ago.

18:19.360 --> 18:22.740
I wrote a short story for weird tales called The Black Ferris.

18:24.000 --> 18:31.760
And I've always been in love with carnivals and circuses and illustrated men and wars and picnics and you name it.

18:32.500 --> 18:35.480
So over the years all this material accumulated.

18:35.720 --> 18:42.180
And one night about 24 years ago, Gene Kelly invited me over to MGM Studios here

18:42.180 --> 18:45.280
to see a new film of his called Invitation to the Dance.

18:45.440 --> 18:52.900
And part of that film is a sort of dance ballet concerned with a clown, a carnival,

18:53.360 --> 18:59.080
sort of material that Lon Cheney Sr. once did 60 years ago in American films.

18:59.240 --> 19:07.180
He did a lot of films about circuses and armless, legless performers,

19:07.180 --> 19:12.760
all kinds of grotesques that he worked with and pretended to imitate.

19:13.420 --> 19:18.860
So I came out of the screening of Gene Kelly's film and walked home with my wife,

19:19.580 --> 19:24.360
lamenting all the way the fact that I'd never worked for Kelly and wanting very much to do so.

19:24.940 --> 19:30.360
So I got home and I rummaged through all my material to find something to send to Gene Kelly.

19:30.360 --> 19:41.520
And I found the black ferris and I took several weeks to write it into a longer 70 page screen adaptation treatment outline.

19:41.960 --> 19:47.040
And I took it to Kelly and he immediately said, my God, I must direct this.

19:47.500 --> 19:51.100
Can I have an option on it? I'll take it to Europe and try to get some money.

19:51.640 --> 19:56.400
He went to Europe for a number of weeks and months and finally returned and said, it's no use.

19:56.520 --> 19:58.500
Nobody wants to put up any money for this.

19:58.500 --> 20:01.060
Thanks very much and so long.

20:01.700 --> 20:06.260
Well, I was heartbroken because I wanted to work for Kelly and I sat the heck with it.

20:06.600 --> 20:11.100
I sat down and I wrote the long screen treatment into a novel.

20:11.300 --> 20:19.320
It took me about two years and the novel was published in the late summer of 1962, 20 years ago.

20:20.260 --> 20:23.540
The novel is a good example of Bradbury's beautifully poetic style.

20:23.540 --> 20:28.100
It uses images of autumn and the gaudy colors of a carnival to convey hidden menace and evil.

20:28.720 --> 20:34.820
The carnival rides, for instance, do strange things to people and the sideshow freaks and grotesques have unnatural horrifying powers.

20:35.380 --> 20:39.000
Bradbury often uses carnival material as a symbol of evil. We asked him why.

20:40.700 --> 20:44.700
I think most of us are uncomfortable around carnivals and circuses.

20:44.800 --> 20:47.920
We sense that the people who run them are evil people.

20:48.100 --> 20:51.520
There is something wrong with most carnival people.

20:51.520 --> 20:56.600
The workers, it's a very tough life. It's a rough existence.

20:58.180 --> 21:05.120
It's run by a bunch of tramps and vagabonds and people who go from town to town, they have no roots.

21:06.840 --> 21:11.860
I should imagine there's a lot that goes on beyond the behind the scenes. We can't even guess that.

21:12.860 --> 21:16.660
Not that there isn't a hierarchy there and a big circus, of course, there is.

21:16.660 --> 21:22.220
There are the people at the top of the hierarchy or the trapeze people. They are the royal family.

21:22.620 --> 21:28.400
Then you go downwards through the various levels of performers depending on their athletic powers.

21:28.680 --> 21:35.900
But it's a very difficult life and it's a miracle if most of these people make it through and keep their sanity.

21:36.520 --> 21:43.860
When you're a child, you sense, especially in the seedy little carnivals that come to visit your hometown,

21:43.860 --> 21:55.220
you sense the uneasiness, the sly life, the sense of evil behind the scenes in these people.

21:55.580 --> 22:00.200
I suppose that's where my fictions came from.

22:00.940 --> 22:06.600
Something wicked this way comes is being made into a major motion picture by Disney Studios and should be out at the end of the year.

22:06.940 --> 22:09.220
We'll continue next time with the works of Ray Bradbury.

