This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

23:41.000 --> 23:42.640
And here are your hosts.

23:47.020 --> 23:48.200
This is David Carson.

23:48.440 --> 23:49.140
And Daryl Lane.

23:49.440 --> 23:52.480
One of Ray Bradbury's classic novels is Fahrenheit 451.

23:52.920 --> 23:58.740
It's a chilling picture of a future society in which books are outlawed and humans are weakened by addiction to a totally electronic society.

23:59.480 --> 24:07.440
A person who possesses a book is subject to severe punishment and there's even a government institution composed of firemen whose job it is to seek out all books and burn them.

24:07.440 --> 24:12.560
We asked Bradbury if there was a particular episode or inspiration behind Fahrenheit 451.

24:37.440 --> 24:43.320
We asked him to write a few American books off of foreign library shelves in army libraries.

24:43.560 --> 24:49.600
And then President Eisenhower ordered them all put back on, which proved what a bright man he was.

24:49.820 --> 24:50.300
Thank goodness.

24:51.100 --> 25:00.140
But he was during that period that I suppose my subconscious permitted on all this and said,

25:00.140 --> 25:13.160
I've got to do a book about my anger about libraries because libraries is really the place where I was born and raised myself, grew up and have lived for a lifetime.

25:13.460 --> 25:15.460
They really are very super special to me.

25:16.480 --> 25:20.260
And I go in bookstores constantly.

25:20.500 --> 25:21.600
I can't stay away from them.

25:21.720 --> 25:22.940
I buy too many books.

25:23.320 --> 25:24.980
I'm compulsive about it.

25:24.980 --> 25:28.340
So the novel wrote itself in nine days.

25:28.780 --> 25:35.100
I went up to UCLA in 19, this is back in 1950.

25:35.540 --> 25:43.640
And I spent nine days there in the typing room in the basement of the UCLA library with about 12 students sitting around me.

25:43.820 --> 25:47.940
And I played these dime a half hour typewriter machines.

25:47.940 --> 25:55.520
And I typed the novel on those dime machines and I spent around $9.40 typing the novel.

25:56.140 --> 26:00.520
So it's a grand place to write a book like that, isn't it, in the basement of a library.

26:01.700 --> 26:05.480
Bradbury seems to be pointing out the dangers of a technological society in the novel.

26:05.940 --> 26:09.680
And some of his other work, like the Martian Chronicles, has some of the same warnings.

26:10.440 --> 26:12.500
We asked him if his work is anti-technological.

26:13.560 --> 26:17.500
Well, that's a misinterpretation. It's never been true.

26:17.980 --> 26:22.340
I've never mistrusted technology as only people. There's a big difference there.

26:22.660 --> 26:25.360
It's the way we use the automobile, for instance.

26:25.560 --> 26:30.480
There's nothing wrong with cars that having more safe drivers won't change.

26:31.620 --> 26:39.700
Now, when it comes to computers, space travel, IBM's electric typewriters, these are all beautiful.

26:39.700 --> 26:45.700
We're using them well. And the future is very exciting because of it.

26:46.340 --> 26:49.500
Now, I've tried to pick those technologies that I criticized.

26:50.180 --> 27:00.040
For instance, there was a certain moment in history in Los Angeles where they were threatening to put Muzak with advertising on our buses.

27:00.800 --> 27:05.440
And I immediately mounted a campaign with some friends, thousands of people who said,

27:05.440 --> 27:09.180
oh, no, you don't. Bad enough we have all these posters all over the place.

27:09.420 --> 27:16.240
But to trap us on buses, then, make us listen to music we don't want to hear, or advertisements we don't want to hear.

27:17.500 --> 27:23.840
So I'm anti the way that particular technology was going to be used.

27:24.860 --> 27:28.520
We asked Bradbury if he thought there was any danger of book burning or censorship today.

27:29.380 --> 27:35.500
We hear those rumors every year. And there are always some stupid librarians, some stupid mayor,

27:36.080 --> 27:42.800
or some dumb pressure group in some town somewhere in our country every year for the last 60 years.

27:42.980 --> 27:47.940
If it wants to censor this, it censor that. And then they blow away. They're just chaffin' the wind.

27:48.540 --> 27:53.840
And don't pay any attention to them. And if they grow giant size, call me on the phone.

27:53.900 --> 27:56.120
I'll come over and kick them in the kishkis. Okay?

